# CONSULT-43 Lateral Seat — Output

Angle: non-obvious mechanisms for a D3D9-only one-frame positional snap at the cantina door.
Honoring all LOCKED facts and BANNED frames. All hypotheses grounded in source file:line.

---

## Mechanism 1: D3DX FPU state corruption changes float-precision of the portal Y math mid-frame (D3D9-exclusive side-effect)

### Hypothesis

The D3D9 plugin (gl05/gl07) calls `D3DXMatrixMultiply` from the legacy d3dx9 SDK on
EVERY frame at `Direct3d9.cpp:3291` inside `setWorldToCameraTransform`, which runs
during the draw phase of `Game.cpp:1199-1228`. This codebase already documents that
D3DX functions disturb the FPU control word — the `_fpreset`/SEH wrapper at
`Direct3d9_VertexShaderData.cpp:87-114` was built precisely because D3DX's own shader
compiler unmasks FP exceptions and resets precision during its post-compile FWAIT, and
`Report.cpp:166-168` has a known hack to restore the FPU after `OutputDebugString` resets
it to 53-bit precision.

`FloatingPointUnit::install` at `FloatingPointUnit.cpp:45-56` sets the x87 FPU to
24-bit single precision (`PRECISION_24 = 0x0000`) with all exceptions masked
(fpcw=0x007f). If `D3DXMatrixMultiply` or any D3DX call inside the D3D9 plugin
temporarily widens precision to 64-bit (`PRECISION_64 = 0x0300`) or 53-bit
(`PRECISION_53 = 0x0200`) BEFORE returning to the simulation code, arithmetic in
`CollisionUtils::transformToCell` (which is called FROM the simulation alter loop, which
runs in the SAME main thread as the draw, but BEFORE the draw; see `Game.cpp:1136/1168`)
would not be affected by the current frame's D3DX call.

HOWEVER: the disturbing direction goes the other way. `FloatingPointUnit::update()` is
called at `Os.cpp:705` inside `Os::processMessages`, which is called inside
`IoWinManager::processEvents(elapsedTime)` at `Game.cpp:1168` — AFTER the alter/collision
phase but BEFORE the draw. If any D3DX call in the D3D9 plugin during the PREVIOUS
frame's draw left the FPU in a wider-precision mode (64-bit), and the engine's
`FloatingPointUnit::update()` / `Report.cpp` guard failed to catch it before the NEXT
frame's collision/portal math runs, the portal Y arithmetic would execute at 64-bit
(extended) precision instead of 24-bit. 64-bit precision changes floating-point
comparison thresholds and rounding — specifically, the portal-crossing line test in
`CellProperty::Notification::positionChanged` uses the START and END positions of the
movement segment. At the exact boundary of a door plane, a 64-bit vs 24-bit comparison
can flip which side of the plane the segment is deemed to end on, changing whether a
portal crossing fires on THIS frame or the NEXT, and therefore whether
`CollisionResolve::resolveCollisions` sees `m_cellA != m_cellB` on the SAME frame as the
player physically crosses the door.

The D3D11 plugin does NOT call D3DX at all — it uses DirectXMath (XMMatrixTranspose via
`Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:1868`) and D3DCompile, both of which are modern Win SDK
code that does not touch the x87 FPU on 32-bit builds. So D3D11 never introduces this
per-frame FPU precision perturbation.

### File:line evidence

- `Direct3d9.cpp:3291` — `D3DXMatrixMultiply` called every frame in `setWorldToCameraTransform`
- `Direct3d9_VertexShaderData.cpp:77-114` — documented D3DX FPU exception unmasking,
  `_fpreset()` guard; confirms D3DX disturbs FPU state in this build
- `Report.cpp:162-168` — documented `OutputDebugString` resets FPU to 53-bit; same pattern
- `FloatingPointUnit.cpp:45-56` — engine sets 24-bit precision; `update()` at :100-111 can
  DETECT drift but only restores if `currentStatus != status`; there is a one-frame window
  if D3DX stomps the control word AFTER `update()` ran for that frame
- `Os.cpp:705` — `FloatingPointUnit::update()` is called once per frame inside
  `Os::processMessages` -> `IoWinManager::processEvents`; runs before draw, not after
- `Game.cpp:1168` — `IoWinManager::processEvents` (FPU update happens here)
- `Game.cpp:1199-1227` — draw + present happen AFTER processEvents; D3DX stomps FPU here
- Next frame's collision alter runs before the next draw, so D3DX precision stomp from
  frame N persists into frame N+1's collision math unless `FloatingPointUnit::update()`
  catches it — it will catch it ONLY if the stomp is still active when `processMessages`
  runs again, which requires the stomp to survive through present and the top of the loop
- `dpvsVisibilityQuery_Resolve.cpp:268-269` — DPVS also calls `_controlfp` in DEBUG
  builds (unmasks FP exceptions), adding another FPU perturber in the D3D9 Debug path

### One empirical discriminator

Force the FPU control word back to 24-bit precision (0x007f) IMMEDIATELY after
`Graphics::present()` returns at `Game.cpp:1227` — add one call to
`FloatingPointUnit::setControlWord(FloatingPointUnit::getControlWord())` (or
`_fpreset(); _clearfp();`) as a one-line additive `_DEBUG` probe after the present call.
If the cantina door snap disappears or its frequency drops significantly under D3D9, the
D3DX-induced FPU precision change is a real contributor. This is a zero-logic change —
it does not alter simulation math, only resets FPU state to where the engine believes
it already is.

