## Mechanism 2: Clock::maxFrameTime clamp asymmetrically truncates D3D9 timestep at the portal frame

### Hypothesis

`Clock::update()` at `Clock.cpp:251-254` clamps `ms_lastFrameTime` to `ms_maxFrameTime`
when the raw QPC delta exceeds the cap (which is `1 / minFrameRate`; defaults from config).
If `minFrameRate=15` (a common SWG default), `ms_maxFrameTime = 1/15 ≈ 66.7 ms`.

Under D3D9 with vsync ON (Run B in the Cycle-9 data — the WORST case, 8/10 snap), the
present call is `D3DPRESENT_INTERVAL_ONE` with `SwapEffect=COPY`, 1 backbuffer
(`Direct3d9.cpp:2230/2255-2256`). On Win11/NVIDIA in windowed mode, this can produce
frame times significantly LARGER than 16.6 ms in certain vblank-interrupt states (the
"stall indefinitely" risk noted in `client_d.cfg:69-71`). If a frame takes e.g. 100 ms
(D3D9 stall), `Clock::update` clamps to ~66 ms and the next frame starts with a large
timestep.

Under D3D11 FLIP_DISCARD 2-buffer `Present(1,0)` (`Direct3d11_Device.cpp:1137`), the
present returns promptly (DXGI flip model does not stall in windowed mode on Win11), so
frame times stay ~16-20 ms and never approach the clamp. The D3D11 path therefore NEVER
gets the clamped 66 ms timestep that D3D9 occasionally produces.

The critical interaction: `CollisionResolve::resolveCollisions`'s rewind magnitude scales
with the penetration depth = velocity * elapsedTime. A clamped 66 ms timestep vs a
normal 16 ms timestep is a 4x difference in penetration depth at the door plane. The
Cycle-9 smoking gun (vsync-ON worse than vsync-OFF) is consistent: `INTERVAL_ONE`
produces LARGER, steadier timesteps than `INTERVAL_IMMEDIATE` on Win11/NVIDIA windowed,
not just tighter — the windowed vblank polling produces systematic overshoots that
`INTERVAL_IMMEDIATE` avoids by not waiting at all. So it is not just "bigger average
timestep" but OCCASIONAL LARGE SPIKES at vblank-miss moments that push the penetration
over the perceptible threshold.

The LOCKED data point from Cycle-3 (FPS cap 30 vs 250 had "maybe slight" effect) is
consistent here too: a global NVIDIA FPS cap changes AVERAGE rate without changing the
per-frame jitter pattern that windowed D3D9 vblank polling produces — a capped-to-30
D3D9 with INTERVAL_ONE windowed still has the exact same per-frame stall risk, just a
different average. D3D11 flip model does not have this stall path at all.

This mechanism is ADDITIVE to the timestep-modulation root cause from Cycle 9 — it
explains the specific SPIKE characteristic of the snap (fires ~80% at vsync-ON, not
100%) better than a smooth "bigger average timestep" argument: it is the stochastic
vblank-miss events that push individual frames over the threshold.

### File:line evidence

- `Clock.cpp:251-254` — maxFrameTime clamp: `if (ms_lastFrameTime > ms_maxFrameTime) ms_lastFrameTime = ms_maxFrameTime`
- `Direct3d9.cpp:2230` — `SwapEffect = D3DSWAPEFFECT_COPY` (windowed)
- `Direct3d9.cpp:2253-2256` — `INTERVAL_IMMEDIATE` (vsync OFF) vs `INTERVAL_ONE` (vsync ON)
- `Direct3d11_Device.cpp:1137` — `Present(1,0)` with `DXGI_SWAP_EFFECT_FLIP_DISCARD`,
  2 buffers (`Device.cpp:560-577`) — DXGI flip model does not stall in windowed Win11
- `client_d.cfg:69-71` — documented "Modern NVIDIA drivers emulate windowed vsync in
  user-space; it can stall indefinitely when the compositor vblank signal is interrupted"
  — confirms the per-frame stall risk is KNOWN and D3D9-specific in this setup
- `Game.cpp:1092` — `elapsedTime = Clock::frameTime()` — the clamped value drives ALL
  per-frame alter calls including player movement and collision integration
- `CollisionResolve.cpp:320` — `resetPos = moveSeg.getBegin(moveSeg.m_cellB)`;
  penetration depth (and therefore rewind magnitude) scales directly with the per-frame
  move distance = velocity * elapsedTime

### One empirical discriminator

Log `Clock::frameTime()` values in a ring buffer of the last 10 frames, then at every
`CollisionResolve::resolveCollisions` RR_Resolved branch log the current `elapsedTime`
alongside the rewind delta magnitude. Prediction: the D3D9 snapping frames will show a
preceding frame time spike (>20 ms), while D3D11 non-snapping frames will show a flat
~16-17 ms cadence. This is an additive one-liner inside the existing CORNERSNAP-RESOLVE
`#ifdef _DEBUG` block — log `Clock::frameTime()` alongside the existing before/after
position — no new instrumentation infrastructure needed.

